WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.280
[Amit Varma]: What's in front of me right now? It's a microphone. I can see it clearly. There's also a laptop

00:00:09.280 --> 00:00:13.760
[Amit Varma]: in front of me. I can see that clearly as well. It's not a horse. Acer does not make

00:00:13.760 --> 00:00:18.480
[Amit Varma]: horses. The laptop is on a table. The table is on the floor. The floor is in a box in

00:00:18.480 --> 00:00:23.160
[Amit Varma]: the sky in a city that people call Mumbai. There are many boxes in the sky. And sometimes

00:00:23.160 --> 00:00:27.400
[Amit Varma]: I walk out of my box and meet friends who have stepped outside of their boxes to meet

00:00:27.400 --> 00:00:33.400
[Amit Varma]: me. And then we find all of us live in different cities in different worlds. And the certainties

00:00:33.400 --> 00:00:39.100
[Amit Varma]: that I can embrace about mics and laptops and tables cannot extend to the outside world.

00:00:39.100 --> 00:00:44.240
[Amit Varma]: Everything is complicated. The universe contains multitudes. As this earth rotates and revolves,

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:49.400
[Amit Varma]: my head begins to spin. I want certainties. So I start building them about the world around

00:00:49.400 --> 00:00:54.640
[Amit Varma]: me. Soon, I have a story to explain everything. The world makes sense again. You also might

00:00:54.640 --> 00:00:59.280
[Amit Varma]: have a story that explains everything. And if I find your story is not the same as mine,

00:00:59.280 --> 00:01:04.200
[Amit Varma]: I can say that you are wrong. I can say that you are evil. And thus comfortable in our

00:01:04.200 --> 00:01:09.400
[Amit Varma]: certainties, we can lose the comfort of friends. My point here is this, the world is difficult

00:01:09.400 --> 00:01:14.360
[Amit Varma]: to make sense of. And it is tempting to fall for a story that offers certainties. This

00:01:14.360 --> 00:01:18.560
[Amit Varma]: could be religion, this could be ideology, this could be a conspiracy theory about the

00:01:18.560 --> 00:01:24.360
[Amit Varma]: seen and the unseen being a plot to take over the world. And even for a writer and ex journalist

00:01:24.360 --> 00:01:30.080
[Amit Varma]: like me, it's tempting to say, stop thinking boss, too much effort, order the seafood platter,

00:01:30.080 --> 00:01:34.360
[Amit Varma]: get the pina colada. I think we all have that urge, don't we? As the famous lines from Kashi

00:01:34.360 --> 00:01:40.000
[Amit Varma]: Kashi go, bhaar mein jaye duniya, hum bhajaye harmoniya. That's why it's so important to

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:45.740
[Amit Varma]: seek out questions instead of answers. That's what I try to do on the show. And so does

00:01:45.740 --> 00:01:54.920
[Unknown]: my guest today. Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics

00:01:54.920 --> 00:02:02.560
[Amit Varma]: and behavioral science. Please welcome your host, Amit Bharma.

00:02:02.560 --> 00:02:06.280
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen. My guest today is the outstanding journalist Rukmini

00:02:06.280 --> 00:02:12.040
[Amit Varma]: S, who was on the show in October 2020, to talk about her pioneering data journalism,

00:02:12.040 --> 00:02:16.520
[Amit Varma]: as well as her teenage years in a rock band. After that episode, Rukmini went on to write

00:02:16.520 --> 00:02:21.400
[Amit Varma]: a book called Whole Numbers and Half Truths, which uses rigorous data to take a good hard

00:02:21.400 --> 00:02:26.920
[Amit Varma]: look at our multitudes. The chapter titles themselves indicate the sweep of the book,

00:02:26.920 --> 00:02:32.120
[Amit Varma]: what India thinks, feels and believes, how India really votes, how India works, how India

00:02:32.120 --> 00:02:38.000
[Amit Varma]: is growing and aging, and so on. What makes this book so enlightening is her approach.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:43.560
[Amit Varma]: She gets into every issue without preconceptions or biases. She's open to letting the data

00:02:43.560 --> 00:02:48.800
[Amit Varma]: speak for itself, even when it indicates patterns that make her uncomfortable. The result is

00:02:48.800 --> 00:02:53.760
[Amit Varma]: a book that contains many truths that seem counterintuitive to us, that fly in the face

00:02:53.760 --> 00:02:58.240
[Amit Varma]: of received wisdom. The episode I released a couple of weeks ago with Shreyana Bhattacharya

00:02:58.240 --> 00:03:03.600
[Amit Varma]: on the loneliness of the Indian woman was full of insights that made me stop and think.

00:03:03.600 --> 00:03:09.600
[Amit Varma]: So is this conversation. For example, until I recorded with Rukmini, I did not know that

00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:17.600
[Amit Varma]: 98% of the sexual violence committed against women in India is legal. 98%. There's a lot

00:03:17.600 --> 00:03:22.920
[Amit Varma]: else in her work that will surprise you and perhaps alarm you about India. But one thing

00:03:22.920 --> 00:03:27.280
[Amit Varma]: that does make me optimistic is that there are still journalists like Rukmini around

00:03:27.280 --> 00:03:32.360
[Amit Varma]: who are questioning everything, searching for truth, trying to go deep. Before we get

00:03:32.360 --> 00:03:35.720
